statement.p:
Which of the given functions is a solution to \frac{dy}{dt}=-k(y+A)?




y = -A + C e^{-kt}




y = A + C e^{-kt}




y = -A + C e^{kt}




y = A^{-1} + C e^{Akt}




y = A + C e^{kt}




y = A^{-1} + C e^{-Akt}

Find an equation of the curve that satisfies 
\frac{dy}{dx} = 70 yx^{6} 
and whose y-intercept is 3.

static.solution:
\displaystyle c_n = \frac{f^{(n)}(0)}{n!}, e.g. 



\displaystyle c_0 = \frac{f(0)}{0!} = 0. 



\displaystyle c_1 = \frac{f'(0)}{1!}; 



\displaystyle f'(x)=5 \arctan(3 x) + 5 x\frac{1}{(3 x)^2+1}3 
= 5 \arctan(3 x) + \frac{15 x}{9 x^2+1}; 



c_1 = 0.



\displaystyle c_2 = \frac{f''(0)}{2!}; 



\displaystyle 
f''(x) = \left( 5 \arctan(3 x) + \frac{15 x}{9 x^2+1} \right)' 



\displaystyle = 
\frac{15}{9 x^2+1} + \frac{15(9 x^2+1)-15 x9\cdot 2x}{(9 x^2+1)^2}



\displaystyle
= \frac{135 x^2 + 15}{(9 x^2+1)^2} + \frac{15 - 135 x^2}{(9 x^2+1)^2}
= \frac{30}{(9 x^2+1)^2};



\displaystyle c_2 = \frac{30}{2} = 15;



and so on. Another way is to use the power series for arctan:  



\displaystyle \arctan(t) = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \frac{t^{2n+1}}{2n+1} 
= t-\frac{t^3}{3}+\frac{t^5}{5}-\frac{t^7}{7}+....



Then 



\displaystyle 5 x \arctan(3 x) = 
5 x \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{(3 x)^{2n+1}}{2n+1} = 
\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{5\cdot 3^{2n+1}}{2n+1} x^{2n+2}
\displaystyle  
= 15 x^2 - \frac{135}{3} x^4 + \frac{1215}{5} x^6 - \frac{10935}{7} x^7+.... 



So c_0=0, c_1=0, c_2=15, c_3=0, c_4=-\frac{135}{3}=-45...



This is an alternating series. It converges if and only if 
\displaystyle \lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{5 \cdot (3 x)^{2n+1}}{2n+1}=0. 
This limit is equal to 0 if and only if |3 x| \le 1, 
so \displaystyle |x|\le \frac{1}{3}. 
Therefore the radius of convergence is \displaystyle \frac{1}{3}.
